 <methods><methodStep><description><section><title>Informa&#231;&#245;es sobre M&#233;todos de Coleta</title>
 <para>Seguindo as informa&#231;&#245;es dispon&#237;veis em Renn&#243; et al. (2008), o c&#225;lculo da dist&#226;ncia vertical &#224; drenagem mais pr&#243;xima foi aplicado para o Interfl&#250;vio Purus-Madeira. No entanto, as informa&#231;&#245;es al&#233;m dos limites dos rios Purus e Madeira na dire&#231;&#227;o Leste e Oeste, e das cidades de Manaus e Humait&#225;, no sentido Norte-Sul, devem ser interpretadas com cautela, pois essas &#225;reas n&#227;o foram corrigidas ou validadas com informa&#231;&#245;es de campo. Com o programa Terraview (http://www.dpi.inpe.br/terraview/index.php), n&#243;s obtivemos os produtos anteriores necess&#225;rios ao calculo da dist&#226;ncia vertical. Os produtos s&#227;o o MDE SRTM-corrigido, as dire&#231;&#245;es de drenagens locais (local drain directions &#8211; LDD), a &#225;rea de drenagens acumulada (ACC) e a rede de drenagens. Diferentemente do LDD e do ACC que dependem apenas do MDE SRTM para serem gerados, a rede de drenagens &#233; um dado que depende de dados de campo para valida&#231;&#227;o ou de um conhecimento pr&#233;vio do pesquisador sobre a &#225;rea de estudo, pois esse conhecimento pr&#233;vio ir&#225; determinar a densidade dessa rede. Ap&#243;s a defini&#231;&#227;o da densidade da rede de drenagens utilizamos o programa hand_grid (http://www.dpi.inpe.br/~camilo/hand/hand_grid.sav) para calcular a dist&#226;ncia vertical &#224; drenagem mais pr&#243;xima, sendo o produto salvo no formato geotiff, com resolu&#231;&#227;o espacial de 3 arcos de segundo ou 0,00083 graus (cerca de 90 m pr&#243;ximo a linha do Equador). Para um detalhamento de como os c&#225;lculos foram feitos, consultar Renn&#243; et al (2008).</para>
 <para>O Hand est&#225; disponibilizado para os seguintes limiares: 10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 100, 150, 200, 250, 300, 350, 400, 450, 500, 600, 700, 800, 900, 1000. O arquivo com o final .tif pode ser aberto em qualquer programa de Sensoriamento Remoto.</para>
 </section>
 </description>
 </methodStep>
 <methodStep><description><section><title>Methods of data collection</title>
 <para>We applied the Height Above the Nearest Drainage algorithm for the Purus-Madeira Interfluve according to the protocol described in Renn&#243; et al. (2008). The pre-processing products were obtained through the Terraview software (http://www.dpi.inpe.br/terraview/index.php). On the SRTM DEM we calculate the Local Drain Direction (LDD), accumulating contributing area (ACC) and the Drainage network. The LDD and the ACC don&#8217;t need external validation and are extracted direct from the SRTM DEM. However, the drainage network extraction depends of field data for validation, because the density of the drainage network varies according to the terrain characteristics and a single drainage threshold can hardly be considered the best representation of a wide heterogeneous area such the Purus-Madeira Interfluve. Eighteen drainage thresholds were chosen as an attempt to overcome this problem. For each drainage network we applied the Height Above the Nearest Drainage (HAND) algorithm using the software hand_grid (http://www.dpi.inpe.br/~camilo/hand/hand_grid.sav) to calculate the vertical distance to the nearest drainage. The products have a spatial resolution of 3 arcseconds (approximately 90 m close to Ecuador), measuring 7200 columns by 6000 rows, and are available in geoTIFF format. For more details, see Renn&#243; et al (2008).</para>
 <para>The HAND dataset were calculated for the following thresholds: 10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 100, 150, 200, 250, 300, 350, 400, 450, 500, 600, 700, 800, 900, 1000. SRTM DEM information can be found in Farr et al (2000) and refers to data generated in 2000. The HAND application was done in November of 2011and it is not possible to know which season the models are representing, since they don&#8217;t detect temporal variation of the water level of the drainages, but their vertical distance to the nearest drainage.</para>
 </section>
 </description>
 </methodStep>
